PS1-3. Data Exploration¶

The adult.csv file contains 9,412 observations with 8 attributes, each representing a demographic characteristic of adults in the United State.

  • Interval-scaled Numeric Attribute: age, education, hours/week
  • Ordinal Attribute: income
  • Nominal Attribute: workclass, marital status, race, sex

Upon checking the five-point descriptive summary data for numeric variables, the measure of central tendency and data dispersion for those are studied. Boxplot and histogram were used to verify the initial assumption based on descriptive data.

Descriptive Analysis for Numerical Variables¶

Solutions for PS1 Part 1 and PS2

I. Five-Point Statistics Analysis¶

The age variable is expected to be slightly postively skewed, where the mean occurs at a value of 38.4 years old which is greater than the median age of 37 and the mode value of 38 years old. The quartiles give a clear indication of the age distribution, with 50% of the observations lies within the interquartile range of 28 to 47 years old. Based on the IQR, there are many outlying observations lying above the upper whisker fence of 75.5 years old. The standard deviation of approximately 13 indicates the age data are more spread out, while 68% of the age value are at the range of 25 to 51 years old.

The education variable is expected to skewed to the right since the mode occurs at a value of 9, slightly smaller than the median of 10 and the mean of 10.1. Based on the IQR of 4, there will be some outliers lying below the lower whisker fence of 5. The standard deviation of approximately 2.5 indicates the datapoints are clustered around the mean value of 10. The statistics suggest that 68% of the education values are at the range of 7.5 to 12.5, indicating a low variation.

The hours/week variable is expected to have a roughly symmetric data distribution, where the mean, median, and the mode are all at the same center value of 40. Worth noting, the lowest quartile also has a value of 40, meaning only 25% of the data falls below the mean. Based on the IQR of 5, there are numbers of outliers lying above the upper whisker fence of 50. The standard deviation of approximately 12 indicates the hours/week data are more spread out, while 68% of the value are at the range of 30 to 52 hours.

II. Measure of Central Tendency¶

Histogram is chosen to summarize the discrete data that are measured on an interval scale, allowing to see the frequency distribution and variability for a large dataset in a clear picture.

For the age variable, the postively skewed unimodal histogram indicates that many of the age value are near the lower end of the quantiles. The elder adults are less frequent in the dataset, often shown as outliers at the high values.

For the education variables, a negatively skewed bimodal histogram is presented as below, where there are two distinct frequent values exist in the dataset. Notice that the skewness is different from the previous assumption; further indicates the mode does not reflect any bimodailty in the population from which the sample was taken. The right-skewed distribution indicates its values are more spread out on the lower end. The gap at the value of 12 might results from that most people decide to go to college after graduating from high school. In a nutshell, there are more observations of adults who received at least 9 years of education.

Lastly, the histogram for the hours/week variable shows a roughly symmetric distribution with one peak point at 40. The graph indicates that there are more outlying observations with people working much more hours than the average working hours of 40 per week, comparing to those who work much less hours than the average working hours.

III. Measure of Data Dispersion¶

Boxplot is chosen to visualize the data dispersion, as it incorporates the five-point data with three quartiles, two whiskers, and individually plotted outliers.

Looking at the boxplot for age variable, the higher whisker is extended to approxiamtely 75, with observations with values that are greater than 1.5*IQR beyond the higher quartile. Notice that there are many outlying observations plotted around the range of 75-90, indicating there is a greater variability among the elder adults in the dataset.

The boxplot for the education variable is more intersting to study. As the median is closer to the bottom of the interquantile box, the distribution of education variable is skewed. Meantime, as the whisker is longer on the lower end of the box, observations for the education are varied amongst the least positive quartile group, while more similar for the most positive quartile. In addition, the variable has two smaller outliers, which is much less than the other two numerical variables.

Lastly, the boxplot for hours/week variable indicates that there is a less variability in terms of distribution, as the middle 50% of the values tend to be clustered arounf the median. However, a significant number of outliers are present on both side of the box. Since, the median is in the exact Q1 quartile, the data distribution is skewed.

IV. Relationship with Numerical Variables¶

To determine whether a relationship or correlation exists among pairwise continuous variables, the Pearson correlation coefficient and pairwise scatterplots are examined. Based on the output below, there are little or very weak associations between all pairwise variables. In other words, the relationship is not predictable as the value of one numerical variables cannot be determined from the value of the other.

  • Age vs. Education Variable Looking at the pairwise scatterplot of age vs. education, it shows haphazard points that follow no direction. In other words, as age variables increases, there is no expectation of what the education variable will change; and vice versa.

  • Age vs. Hours/Week The scatterplot of age vs hours/week variable shows that there is no correlation relationship between the two attributes in each of the given datasets. The location of each dot on the scatterplot represents one observation/adult in the dataset, which its locations are dependent on both their age and working hours per week. Notice that for a given value of age, the corresponding values of hours/week range all over the place; hence, no relationship is detected. In addition, we run into the issue of overplotting where there are too many datapoints overlapping, making it difficult to see the clear trend.

  • Education vs. Hours/week Interestingly, shown in the scatterplot, there is a lack of predictability in determining hours/week from a given value of education. The non-structured scatterplot indicate there is no relationship exists between the two attributes.

I. Frequency Distribution of Categorical Variables¶

  • The workclass variable contains 3 unique values, including private, public, and self-employeed, where the most frequent recorded value being private.
  • The marital-status variable contains 2 unique values, including married and single. Although married is the more commonly occurred value, the difference between that and the frequency for single is not significant.
  • The race variable contains 5 unique values, with the most commonly occurred value being white. There are more white adults observed in the dataset than observations from the rest of race combined. Notice that there are much fewer observations for Hispanic and American-Indian than the other race, which might lead to unaccountable conclusions for those two race groups.
  • The sex variable contains 2 unique values, including male and female. Based on the frequency table, there are at least as twice observations from male adults as the females.
  • Lastly, the income variable contains 2 unique values, including adults who make less or equal than 50k per year, and those who makes greater than 50k per year. Based on the output, adults who makes less or equal than 50k/year outnumbered those who make greater than 50k/per by a significant margin.

PS4. Cross Tabulations of Workclass & Race & Income¶

I. Workclass vs. Race¶

The contingency table below describes observation frequencies by their workclass and identified race. At a glance, there are far more job demands in the private sector than others, regardless of race. The most frequent occuring category is white adults who works in the private sector, with 5,950 observations, while there are only 5 Hispanic adults who works in the public sector. Interstingly, 6 Hispanic adults claim themselves as self-employed, which is slightly more than those who works in the public sector. Hence, one assumption is that Hispanic adults are more likely to be self-employed, comparing to the rest.

II. Workclass vs. Income¶

The contingency table below describes observation frequencies by their workclass and identified income bracket. Upon calculation, only 24.64% of adults in the dataset make more than 50k/year. Interestingly, the conditional probability of an adult who works in the public sector makes more than 50k/year is approximately 30%, while there is an approximately 37% probability for an adult who is self-empolyeed. Thus, the assumption is that self-employed freelancers earn more than those who are traditionally employed.

PS7. Correlation Analysis¶

Since the Pearson correlation method assumes all variables are normally distributed, and the dataset is highly skewed due to outliers, with prescence of ordinal and nominal variables; Kendall's correlation is used to measure the degree of the relationship between linearly related variables. Kendall's correlation is a non-parametric method that does not require continuous or normal distributed data.

Although none of the pairs indicates a very strong correlation, the highest coefficients are plotted as below. Based on the heatmap, the highest pairwised correlation for two distinct attributes is .41, which is among income and marital status. This correlation relationship further proves the assumption that married adults are more likely to earn more than 50k/year than those who are single. Looking at the correlation of education with all other atributes, income>50k has the highest correlation coefficient with education, with a value of .28. Meantime, for adults who make less or equal than 50k/year, they are more likely to be associated with the attribute single.
